abstract: When you travel, is tracking down a fantastic meal just as important as seeing the sights? I have tips to help.
snippet: When you travel, is tracking down a fantastic meal just as important as seeing the sights? I have tips to help.
lead_paragraph: This year seems like a good year for a great trip. On The Times’s Food desk, where I’m an editor and also write a weekly newsletter about New York City restaurants, we’re already scouting for the year’s best restaurants, and I’m guessing many of you are planning trips with food in mind, too.

abstract: A group of scholars introduced an international panel to study the digital information landscape, inspired by those who had been warning of the effect of global warming.
snippet: A group of scholars introduced an international panel to study the digital information landscape, inspired by those who had been warning of the effect of global warming.
lead_paragraph: Two years ago, at a virtual gathering organized by the Nobel Foundation, Sheldon Himelfarb outlined the idea that the world’s leading scholars should join forces to study misinformation the way that scientists of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change documented the global effect of carbon emissions.

main: With Climate Panel as a Beacon, Global Group Takes On Misinformation
print_headline: Global Group Takes On Threat of Misinformation

value: International Panel on the Information Environment

abstract: College students need a taste of the monk’s life.
snippet: College students need a taste of the monk’s life.
lead_paragraph: Nery Rodriguez just graduated from the University of Pennsylvania with a major in economics, but one of the most significant courses she took there had nothing to do with marginal utility or game theory. When she registered last fall for the seminar known around campus as the monk class, she wasn’t sure what to expect.

main: Why Universities Should Be More Like Monasteries

abstract: Senior Democratic lawmakers said the United States should not give $300 million in aid to Egypt until it improves its human rights record, in the latest instance of tensions over Middle East policies.
snippet: Senior Democratic lawmakers said the United States should not give $300 million in aid to Egypt until it improves its human rights record, in the latest instance of tensions over Middle East policies.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — State Department officials said Wednesday that they would give Egypt most of an allocated $300 million in conditional military aid despite pressure from senior Democratic lawmakers to withhold the full amount until the country improves its human rights record.

main: U.S. to Move Forward on Military Aid to Egypt Despite Lawmakers’ Concerns
print_headline: U.S. to Move Forward on Military Aid to Egypt Despite Rights Concerns

name: subject
value: Human Rights and Human Rights Violations

original: By Edward Wong and Vivian Yee

abstract: As the U.S. liaison to some 50,000 United Nations diplomats and staff, he sought to resolve disputes on issues ranging from fugitives hiding in U.N. missions to diplomats’ unpaid parking tickets.
snippet: As the U.S. liaison to some 50,000 United Nations diplomats and staff, he sought to resolve disputes on issues ranging from fugitives hiding in U.N. missions to diplomats’ unpaid parking tickets.
lead_paragraph: Robert C. Moller, a former New York City police detective who as a State Department diplomat spent two decades shielding visiting U.N. delegates from the idiosyncrasies of New York City and vice versa, died on Dec. 6 at his home in Freehold Township, N.J. He was 85.

main: Robert Moller Dies at 85; Mediated Between U.N. Envoys and the City
print_headline: Robert Moller, 85, Ever-Patient Mediator  Between U.N. Envoys and the City, Dies

abstract: Quarterly revenue was up 7 percent and profits were up 9 percent as the company embarked on an aggressive plan to embrace artificial intelligence.

abstract: Name-change documents filed in Texas show that the outspoken entrepreneur recently fathered twins with Shivon Zilis, a director at one of his companies.
snippet: Name-change documents filed in Texas show that the outspoken entrepreneur recently fathered twins with Shivon Zilis, a director at one of his companies.
lead_paragraph: Elon Musk, the billionaire Tesla founder, had twins in November with Shivon Zilis, a director at one of his companies, according to court documents made public on Wednesday. Neither Mr. Musk nor Ms. Zilis has spoken publicly about their children.

main: How Many Children Does Elon Musk Have?

abstract: A selection of recently published books.
snippet: A selection of recently published books.
lead_paragraph: THE JAPANESE MYTHS: A Guide to Gods, Heroes and Spirits, by Joshua Frydman. (Thames & Hudson, $24.95.) A professor of Japanese literature ushers readers through the country’s mythology from the earliest written stories to the rise of the manga industry and situates Japan’s rich cultural tradition within religious and historical developments.
